title: Science
questions[0].q: Which part of the cell is known as the powerhouse of the cell?
questions[1].q: Which law explains the relationship between current, voltage, and resistance?
questions[2].q: Which of the following metals is stored in kerosene?
questions[3].q: Which gas is released during photosynthesis?
questions[4].q: Which device is used to measure electric current?
questions[5].q: Which organ in the human body is responsible for filtering blood?
questions[6].q: What type of lens is used to correct myopia (short-sightedness)?
questions[7].q: Which phenomenon explains the formation of a rainbow?
questions[8].q: What is the chemical formula of quicklime?
questions[9].q: Which mirror is used in the headlights of vehicles?
questions[0].explain: Mitochondria generate energy in the form of ATP, so they are called the powerhouse of the cell.
questions[1].explain: Ohm’s Law states that V = IR, showing the relationship between voltage, current, and resistance.
questions[2].explain: Sodium is highly reactive and reacts with air or moisture, so it is stored in kerosene.
questions[3].explain: During photosynthesis, plants release oxygen as a byproduct.
questions[4].explain: An ammeter is used to measure the flow of electric current in a circuit.
questions[5].explain: Kidneys filter waste products from the blood to form urine.
questions[6].explain: A concave lens diverges light rays, helping to correct myopia.
questions[7].explain: A rainbow is formed due to refraction, reflection, and dispersion of sunlight in water droplets.
questions[8].explain: Quicklime is calcium oxide (CaO). It reacts with water to form slaked lime.
questions[9].explain: Concave mirrors are used in vehicle headlights to focus light into a strong beam.

title: English
questions[0].q: Who is the author of the poem 'The Road Not Taken'?
questions[1].q: What is the figure of speech used in 'The world is a stage'?
questions[2].q: Which of the following is a synonym for 'Brave'?
questions[3].q: Identify the part of speech of the underlined word: She runs *quickly*.
questions[4].q: Which tense is used in the sentence: 'He has finished his homework'?
questions[5].q: Fill in the blank: She is fond ___ music.
questions[6].q: Choose the correct indirect speech: He said, 'I am tired.'
questions[8].q: Which of the following is a complex sentence?
questions[6].options[0].text: He said that he is tired.
questions[6].options[1].text: He said that he was tired.
questions[6].options[2].text: He says that he was tired.
questions[8].options[1].text: Because it was raining, I stayed inside.
questions[0].explain: The poem 'The Road Not Taken' was written by Robert Frost.
questions[1].explain: The phrase compares 'world' to a 'stage' without using 'like' or 'as', so it is a metaphor.
questions[3].explain: The word 'quickly' describes how she runs, so it is an adverb.
questions[4].explain: The helping verb 'has' with past participle 'finished' shows present perfect tense.
questions[6].explain: In reported speech, 'am' changes to 'was'. So, 'He said that he was tired.'
questions[8].explain: A complex sentence has an independent and a dependent clause, like 'Because it was raining, I stayed inside.'

title: Social Science
questions[0].q: Who was the first President of independent India?
questions[1].q: In which year did India get independence?
questions[2].q: Who was known as the Iron Man of India?
questions[3].q: Which river is known as the 'Ganga of the South'?
questions[4].q: Which is the largest democracy in the world?
questions[5].q: Which movement was launched by Mahatma Gandhi in 1942?
questions[6].q: What is the capital of India?
questions[7].q: Which planet is known as the Blue Planet?
questions[8].q: Which fundamental right ensures equality before the law?
questions[9].q: Who wrote the book 'Discovery of India'?
questions[0].explain: Dr. Rajendra Prasad served as the first President of India from 1950 to 1962.
questions[1].explain: India gained independence from British rule on 15th August 1947.
questions[2].explain: Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel is known as the Iron Man of India for his role in uniting the country.
questions[3].explain: The Godavari River is called the 'Ganga of the South' as it is the largest river in peninsular India.
questions[4].explain: India is the largest democracy in the world with the highest number of voters.
questions[5].explain: The Quit India Movement was launched in 1942 demanding an end to British rule.
questions[6].explain: New Delhi is the capital city of India.
questions[7].explain: Earth appears blue from space because of the presence of water bodies.
questions[8].explain: The Right to Equality guarantees equality before the law for all citizens of India.
questions[9].explain: Jawaharlal Nehru wrote 'The Discovery of India' while imprisoned in 1944.

title: Maths
questions[0].q: What is the value of (a + b)²?
questions[1].q: What is the sum of the angles of a triangle?
questions[3].q: What is the value of 15% of 200?
questions[4].q: What is the next prime number after 23?
questions[5].q: If the radius of a circle is doubled, what happens to its area?
questions[7].q: What is the perimeter of a square with side 8 cm?
questions[8].q: What is the value of sin 90°?
questions[9].q: If x = 5, what is the value of 3x + 4?
questions[0].explain: The expansion of (a + b)² is a² + 2ab + b².
questions[1].explain: The sum of angles in any triangle is 180°.
questions[5].explain: Area ∝ r², so doubling radius makes area 4 times.
